"# Chapter 1 — Hello, and a Sound

Every programming book on Earth starts you off printing the word HELLO.

We're going to print HELLO too. It'll take one line.

Then, on line two, we're going to make the computer buzz.

If your speakers are on, you'll hear it. If they're not, the runtime will still promise us it happened, and we'll take its word for it. Either way, by the time you finish this chapter you'll have done something no other Hello World does: you'll have moved air. You'll have made a small piece of the world respond because you asked it to. That is the actual point of this book.

## The three things you need

You need three things to follow along.

1. A terminal — the black window where you type commands.
2. Motoi Scheme installed. If you can type `motoi version` and see a number, you have it.
3. A file. That's it. We'll write our first program in a file called `hello.scm` and run it.

If any of those three are missing, Appendix C at the back of the book walks you through setup in about five minutes. Come back when you're ready.

## The two ways to run Motoi

Motoi gives you two ways to run code, and you'll use both constantly.

**Way one: `motoi eval`.** You give it one expression, on the command line, in quotes. It evaluates that expression and prints the answer. Good for one-liners, sanity checks, trying stuff.

```
$ motoi eval \"(+ 3 4)\"
7
```

Seven. The answer to *three plus four*. Notice the shape: the operator comes first — `+` — then the numbers. Everything in Scheme has that shape. Operator first. Arguments after. Wrap it in parentheses. We'll come back to this five times before the chapter's over — it's the entire grammar of the language.

**Way two: `motoi run somefile.scm`.** You put your program in a file, and Motoi runs the whole thing top to bottom. This is what you'll do when a program grows past one line, which happens fast.

Try both right now, with the tiniest programs possible.

```
$ motoi eval \"(display \\\"hi\\\")\"
hi
```

`display` prints something. The `\\\"` is just how you escape a double quote inside a shell-quoted string — inside the actual Scheme program the string is `\"hi\"`, plain and normal.

Now put a two-liner in a file. Open your text editor, make a file called `hello.scm` right where you are, and type this in:

```
(display \"hi\")
(newline)
```

Save. In the terminal:

```
$ motoi run hello.scm
hi
```

`hi` on one line, then a fresh line after. `newline` is exactly what it sounds like — it hits Return.

Two ways to run code. `eval` for one thought, `run` for a program. From here on when I show you a shell prompt with `$` in front, that's the terminal talking to you. When I show `>` — that's Motoi's REPL, which we'll meet in Chapter 3.

## Hello, then

The classic. In `hello.scm`:

```
(display \"Hello, Motoi\")
(newline)
```

Run it:

```
$ motoi run hello.scm
Hello, Motoi
```

That's the entire ceremony. Two verbs, one string, no boilerplate, no class, no main, no imports. Scheme has almost no ceremony — it's one of the reasons Scheme has been used to teach programming for the last forty years. The language gets out of the way and lets you point at the thing you want the computer to do.

## Now make a sound

The runtime ships with an audio module built in. It knows how to make tones. Try this in the terminal:

```
$ motoi eval \"(audio/play 'tone 440 0.5)\"
ok
```

`audio/play` is a verb — a name Motoi knows. Its first argument here is the symbol `'tone`, which tells it what kind of thing to play. The single quote in front of `tone` means *this is a name, not a variable to look up*. The next two numbers are the frequency in Hertz (440 is the A above middle C, the note orchestras tune to) and the duration in seconds. Play an A for half a second.

Motoi wrote back `ok`. If your speakers are on and up, you heard a short beep. If you didn't, the runtime still queued the sound; it's just that no output device was reachable. This is a real thing to know about audio programming: whether or not you can *hear* the tone is not the same question as whether the *program* worked. The program worked. `ok` said so.

### The most important note in the world

Because we're going to come back to it a hundred times, learn one specific note name right now: **middle C** — the C in the middle of a piano keyboard, the C above the bass staff, the anchor most Western music uses. Middle C is about **261.63 Hz**:

```
$ motoi eval \"(audio/play 'tone 261.63 0.5)\"
ok
```

That form is your canonical middle C. Any time a music program asks for middle C, this line plays it. Chapter 12 will show you four other ways to get the same pitch (with note names, MIDI numbers, and voice tags), but `(audio/play 'tone 261.63 0.5)` always works, always plays middle C, and is the one to reach for when in doubt.

Try a lower note:

```
$ motoi eval \"(audio/play 'tone 220 0.5)\"
ok
```

220 Hertz is an octave below 440. Try higher:

```
$ motoi eval \"(audio/play 'tone 880 0.3)\"
ok
```

880 is an octave above. Play with the numbers. This is your first *loop* — the human loop. Try, listen, adjust, try again. If a program ever behaves in a way you don't expect, this loop is what gets you out of it. We'll go deeper in Chapter 4 (arithmetic) and then again in Appendix E (debugging).

## Two notes make a beep pair

Put a real little program in `sound.scm`:

```
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 660 0.2)
(audio/play 'tone 880 0.2)
```

```
$ motoi run sound.scm
ok
ok
ok
```

Three notes, each played once, each half a second short so they don't run into each other. If you hear them all together instead of in sequence, that's the audio engine deciding to overlap them — different runtimes handle scheduling differently. In Chapter 12 we'll use `audio/tempo` and `note/place-at` to schedule sounds precisely at exact moments. For now, you've told the runtime to make three notes. It did.

The reason each line printed `ok` is that when you run a file, Motoi prints the value of every top-level expression it evaluates. Each `audio/play` call returns the symbol `ok`, and `run` prints it. If you find that noisy, wrap the whole thing in a `begin` and only the last value gets printed:

```
(begin
  (audio/play 'tone 440 0.2)
  (audio/play 'tone 660 0.2)
  (audio/play 'tone 880 0.2))
```

```
$ motoi run sound.scm
ok
```

`begin` is a small keyword that means *do these things in order, and give me back the last one's value*. We'll use it constantly.

## A joke about parentheses

You may have noticed the parentheses.

Yes.

Every book about Scheme has to acknowledge the parentheses within the first five pages. Fine — here it is. Scheme has a lot of parentheses. So does everything else, we've just decided not to see them there. In JavaScript `foo(x, y)` has parentheses. In Python `foo(x, y)` has parentheses. In Scheme it's `(foo x y)` — the left paren just moved. That's the whole difference. Once your eye starts to see parentheses as *the shape of a function call*, they disappear.

More useful thing to notice: the parentheses tell you the *tree* of your program. `(- 100 (* 3 12))` says: I'm going to subtract something from 100, and the thing I'm subtracting is (3 times 12). Read outside-in. The outer paren is the outer operation. This is why Scheme code is so easy to move around, cut, paste, refactor — the parentheses give the tree away. There's no order-of-operations argument to have with yourself. What's inside a paren happens first.

## What just happened, in slow motion

You typed a line. Something in the runtime read that line. It broke it into pieces. It figured out what each piece meant. It did the thing. It gave you an answer.

Four steps. Every Scheme system on Earth does these four:

1. **Read** — turn the text `(+ 3 4)` into a data structure the interpreter can walk. In Scheme this data structure is a *list*. Yes — the language and the data are the same shape. This is called *homoiconicity* and it's why macros (Chapter 9) are so powerful.
2. **Expand** — if any of the forms are macros, run them and get plain code back.
3. **Evaluate** — walk the tree. Look up names. Call functions. Compute.
4. **Print** — take the answer and show it to you.

Read, Expand, Evaluate, Print. R-E-E-P if you want a mnemonic. This is often shortened to REPL — Read, Eval, Print, Loop — when you sit at the prompt and do the whole cycle over and over.

You just did REEP twice: once for the sound, once for the print. Congratulations. You've programmed a computer today. Everything after this is more of the same shape.

## What you know now

- Motoi has two entry points: `motoi eval \"...\"` for a single expression, and `motoi run file.scm` for a program.
- Function calls put the operator first, arguments after, all wrapped in parentheses: `(+ 3 4)`, `(display \"hi\")`.
- `display` prints. `newline` starts a new line. Both are ordinary functions — no magic.
- `audio/play` makes sounds. `(audio/play 'tone 440 0.5)` plays a 440 Hz tone for half a second.
- A single quote in front of a name — `'tone` — means *this is a literal name, don't look up its value*.
- `begin` wraps a sequence of expressions and returns the last one's value.
- The runtime cycles through Read → Expand → Evaluate → Print for every expression.

## Try before you turn the page

Make each of these work. If something doesn't, that's information — take it into Appendix E (debugging) and figure out why.

1. Play three tones in a row, each 0.25 seconds long, at frequencies 262, 330, and 392. If you can name the chord these three notes make together, congratulations — you know a little bit of music theory too. If you can't, we'll cover it in Chapter 12.

2. Write a program in a file called `intro.scm` that prints your name, then a newline, then plays a single 500 Hz tone for one second.

3. Change the last line of your `sound.scm` to play a *very* low tone — 55 Hz — for one full second. If your speakers can handle it, you'll feel it more than hear it. If not, you'll hear a faint rumble. Programming has a texture; audio is one of the fastest ways to feel it.

4. In the terminal, type `motoi eval \"(+ 1 1)\"`. What happens? Now type `motoi eval \"(+ 1)\"`. What happens? Now `motoi eval \"(+)\"`. What happens? The answers will not be what you expect for at least one of those. That's Chapter 4 material — but the point right now is: playing with the edges is how you learn where the edges are.

## What's next

Chapter 2, we move something. Not sound — motion. A dot, a sprite, a little glowing thing that lives somewhere on a grid and can be told where to go. Everything about visualization starts with *placing one thing in one spot*. Once you can do that, you can do animation, and games, and every kind of interactive interface Motoi supports. It builds fast from here.")
